<br>
1) He claims there is no soft cap for armor class. <br>
<br>
2) Also, He claims that armor class is always better than hit points, even when fighting against reds. They don't always do max damage is what he said. <br>
<br>
3) I read a thread about the attack value. It mentioned that the attack value affects different things based on whether it was gained from strength or from an item or spell. Any more information on this would be great. <br>
<br>
I hope you guys can help me out.  Thanks in advance.<br>
<br>
Eledryth Tavaro <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 743<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/24/03 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2813.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need Proof</span><hr size=1> I'm afraid you're going to be disappointed.  Conclusive unquestioned proof does not exist either for or against the existance of an AC soft cap.  The best we've been able to do is show that there seems to be a point were additional AC against certain specifc mobs does not appear to further reduce the number of hits you take or the amount of damage you take from them.  But this does not translate necessarily into a universal AC soft cap.<br>
<br>
We have indications things work a certain way.  Using those indications we've built up a working hypothesis that seems to work most of the time.  That's not conclusive proof though and PoP seems to have changed things yet again.  The jury is still out.<br>
  <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A> at: 1/24/03 12:08:42 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wyrdlan>Wyrdlan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 117<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/24/03 11:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2813.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.eq-viatores.org/book.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Need Proof</span><hr size=1> 1) Sorta true, sorta not.<br>
<br>
It largely depends on what you are fighting.  By soft cap, we usually mean the point where AC isn't worth the effort to get more.  For velious/luclin mobs this is around 1200, for PoP mobs, it's pretty much gone.  More is more.<br>
<br>
<br>
2) Sorta.  Definitely 1 AC is better than 1 HP, but that's rarely the change you'll make.  Also, at 900 AC, 1 AC may be worth another 50 HP, but at 1300 AC it's worth less.  That's more of a feeling it out kind of thing.<br>
<br>
<br>
3) This is definitely true, but I'm not the best to explain it.<br>
<br>
It works sorta like this:  STR raises your attk score, and gives you the chance to hit a little harder for your max hit.  This gives you little more damage.<br>
<br>
Actual ATK buffs, like Spirit of Bih'li or Aura of Battle, Avatar, umm rogue epic... er Boon of the Garu... ummm stuff like that raise how consistently you hit.  This gives you a much more noticable increase in damage.  I'm thinking that 10 ATK is roughly a 1% increase in damage.  This is called raw attack.<br>
<br>
<br>
*edit*  And definitely agree with the guy above me.  I'm trying to explain how most warriors believe it works, based on testing and experience.  Hard proof beyond statistics isn't going to happen. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wyrdlan>Wyrdlan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0> at: 1/24/03 11:46:31 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=daleb123>Daleb123</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/24/03 11:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2813.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Questions</span><hr size=1> 1. Well, yes and no. First, do you understand what the AC soft cap is? It's a point at which adding more AC gives little or no benefit; what makes it &quot;soft&quot; is that there is no fixed value - it depends entirely on the damage potential portion of the opponent's ATK. In general, high-end MOBs have gotten more difficult with each expansion, so we could come up with some approximate value for high-end old world vs Kunark vs Velious...MOBs, but the value really depends on what you are fighting. So there is a soft cap, but there is no fixed value (i.e. no hard cap).<br>
<br>
2. Armor is not always better than hit points. For starters, AC doesn't protect you at all from spells - hit points do. Furthermore, since it has already been established that for any given MOB, there is a point at which more AC doesn't help, hit points will be of more value in such circumstances.<br>
<br>
3. ATK has 2 components - one which affects hit probability, and one which affects damage when you hit. During Beta test, these values were displayed separately, but Verant chose to display a single number in the final version of the game; ATK is the sum of those two numbers. <br>
<br>
ATK is calculated from Offense skill, weapon skill (the ATK value displayed is always for the weapon in your primary hand, but secondary hand weapons have their own which is never displayed to the player), STR, and any +ATK buffs. Each of these may affect one or both of the components. I believe that STR affects damage potential only, Offense skill affects hit probability only, and weapon skill affects both; I have not done enough testing with +ATK buffs, other than to confirm that they affect damage potential.<br>
<br>
